template_id: openagreements-restrictive-covenant-missouri
name: OpenAgreements Employee Restrictive Covenant (Missouri)
category: non-compete
description: >-
  Missouri-specific employee restrictive covenant agreement built for Missouri's
  common-law reasonableness regime: there is no general Missouri non-compete
  statute, so every post-employment restraint begins as a presumptively void
  restraint on trade and is enforceable only to the extent it is demonstrably
  reasonable AND protects the employer's trade secrets or customer contacts —
  never mere competition (Healthcare Servs. of the Ozarks, Inc. v. Copeland;
  Payroll Advance, Inc. v. Yates), with the employer bearing the burden on the
  protectable interest and on time/geographic reasonableness (Whelan Sec. Co.
  v. Kennebrew). It provides confidentiality and trade-secret protection
  backstopped by the Missouri Uniform Trade Secrets Act (Mo. Rev. Stat.
  §§ 417.453, 417.455), an independent-consideration recital reflecting
  Missouri's divided consideration law (Baker v. Bristol Care, Inc.; Durrell v.
  Tech Elecs., Inc.; JumboSack Corp. v. Buyck), a customer non-solicitation
  covenant narrowed to serviced customers rather than the whole customer book
  (Whelan), an employee non-solicitation covenant drawn to the one-year
  conclusive-presumption safe harbor of Mo. Rev. Stat. § 431.202, an optional
  non-compete tied to the identified trade-secret or customer-contact interest
  and sized to the actual footprint, a tolling clause flagged as an open
  Missouri question, physician covenants held to the ordinary Copeland
  reasonableness standard (Missouri has no physician-specific statute), and
  discretionary judicial modification that the drafting does not rely on
  (Whelan permits modification; Sigma-Aldrich Corp. v. Vikin makes it
  discretionary; Paradise v. Midwest Asphalt Coatings, Inc. prices overreach
  through the prevailing-party fee rule). Drafted as a starting point for
  licensed counsel review.
